---
// RoundTripLoop — Chapter 062 Lesson 2, "Move every control to the URL".
//
// The lesson's core mental model: this is a ONE-WAY loop. The URL is *read on the
// server* and *written from the client*. This figure makes that split visible.
//
//   READ PATH (top row, left→right, all on the server except the URL itself):
//     URL ──▶ searchParamsCache.parse ──▶ listInvoices ──▶ rendered list
//
//   WRITE-BACK (the client controls hang under the URL and feed back INTO it):
//     toolbar · tabs · chips · pagination ──[nuqs setters · shallow:false]──▶ URL
//
// Placing the client box directly beneath URL keeps the return arrow a short arc
// in the left margin and drives home the point: every client write re-enters at
// the URL, which re-runs the whole read path. No client-side filtering, no
// duplicated state — the URL is the one place view-state lives.
//
// Built with <ArrowDiagram> (LeaderLine): the boxes are two-line custom HTML (a
// monospace title + a muted under-label) and the read/write arrows carry semantic
// color — the server read path in blue, the client write-back in amber. D2/Mermaid
// plain-label boxes wouldn't carry either. The arrows are positioned from
// document.body, so the wrapping <Figure> MUST be expandable={false}: relocating
// the body into the lightbox breaks the leader lines.
//
// Chrome is theme-aware (Starlight gray/white vars flip light/dark). The two
// accents (#2563eb blue server, #d97706 amber client) are used as-is in both
// themes — mid-tones that read on either background. margin:0 resets defeat
// Starlight's injected prose margins inside the figure.

import Figure from '../../../figures/Figure.astro';
import ArrowDiagram from '../../../figures/ArrowDiagram.astro';

// Mid-tone accents reused verbatim in light + dark.
const SERVER_BLUE = '#2563eb'; // the read path — runs on the server
const CLIENT_AMBER = '#d97706'; // the write-back — runs on the client

// The four read-path boxes, left → right. `under` is the small muted label under
// each title; `tint` flags the server boxes that get the blue wash.
const readBoxes = [
  { id: 'rt-url', title: 'URL', under: 'address bar', server: false },
  {
    id: 'rt-parse',
    title: 'searchParamsCache.parse',
    under: 'server',
    server: true,
  },
  { id: 'rt-list', title: 'listInvoices', under: 'server', server: true },
  {
    id: 'rt-rows',
    title: 'rendered list',
    under: 'server-rendered',
    server: true,
  },
];

const arrows = [
  // READ PATH — three hops left→right along the top row. Short labels name the
  // shape handed across each boundary: raw query string → typed object → rows.
  {
    from: 'rt-url',
    to: 'rt-parse',
    label: 'query string',
    color: SERVER_BLUE,
    startSocket: 'right',
    endSocket: 'left',
    startSocketGravity: [60, 0],
    endSocketGravity: [-60, 0],
    labelOffset: [0, -16],
  },
  {
    from: 'rt-parse',
    to: 'rt-list',
    label: 'ListParsed',
    color: SERVER_BLUE,
    startSocket: 'right',
    endSocket: 'left',
    startSocketGravity: [60, 0],
    endSocketGravity: [-60, 0],
    labelOffset: [0, -16],
  },
  {
    from: 'rt-list',
    to: 'rt-rows',
    label: 'rows',
    color: SERVER_BLUE,
    startSocket: 'right',
    endSocket: 'left',
    startSocketGravity: [60, 0],
    endSocketGravity: [-60, 0],
    labelOffset: [0, -16],
  },
  // WRITE-BACK — the client controls box sits under URL; its setters write the
  // query string and (with shallow:false) make the server re-read. The arrow
  // leaves the client box's top and re-enters URL from the bottom: a short arc in
  // the left margin that closes the loop without crossing the read row.
  {
    from: 'rt-client',
    to: 'rt-url',
    label: 'nuqs setters · shallow:false',
    color: CLIENT_AMBER,
    startSocket: 'top',
    endSocket: 'bottom',
    startSocketGravity: [0, -54],
    endSocketGravity: [0, 54],
    labelOffset: [4, 0],
  },
];
---

<Figure expandable={false}>
  <ArrowDiagram arrows={arrows}>
    <div class="rt not-content">
      {/* READ PATH — server, left → right */}
      <div class="rt-row">
        {
          readBoxes.map((box) => (
            <div class={`rt-box${box.server ? ' rt-box--server' : ''}`} id={box.id}>
              <span class="rt-title">{box.title}</span>
              <span class="rt-under">{box.under}</span>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>

      {/* WRITE-BACK — client controls, parked under URL so the loop is a short arc */}
      <div class="rt-clientrow">
        <div class="rt-box rt-box--client" id="rt-client">
          <span class="rt-title">toolbar · tabs · chips · pagination</span>
          <span class="rt-under">client write-back</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </ArrowDiagram>
  <Fragment slot="caption">
    A one-way loop. The read path — *URL → parse → `listInvoices` → rendered list* —
    runs on the **server**; the toolbar, tabs, chips, and pagination only ever
    write back to the URL from the **client**. Every client write re-enters at the
    URL and re-runs the whole read, so the URL is the one place the view-state lives.
  </Fragment>
</Figure>

<style>
  .rt {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: stretch;
    gap: 64px;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 18px 4px 8px;
    font-family:
      ui-sans-serif, system-ui, -apple-system, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif;
  }

  /* The read row: four boxes, left → right, evenly spaced with room for the
     curve + label in each gap. */
  .rt-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: nowrap;
    align-items: stretch;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 78px;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* The client box is parked under the URL box (the first read-row column), so the
     write-back arrow is a short vertical-ish arc in the left margin. */
  .rt-clientrow {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: flex-start;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .rt-box {
    box-sizing: border-box;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 3px;
    flex: 1 1 0;
    min-width: 0;
    padding: 11px 14px;
    border-radius: 10px;
    border: 1.5px solid var(--sl-color-gray-4, #94a3b8);
    background: var(--sl-color-bg, transparent);
    text-align: center;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Server read boxes — a faint blue wash + blue border ties them to the read
     arrows and reads as "this runs on the server". */
  .rt-box--server {
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, #2563eb 55%, transparent);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, #2563eb 8%, var(--sl-color-bg, transparent));
  }

  /* The client controls box — amber, matched to the write-back arrow. Sized to sit
     under the URL column; capped so it doesn't stretch under the whole row. */
  .rt-box--client {
    flex: 0 0 auto;
    width: clamp(15rem, 38%, 22rem);
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, #d97706 60%, transparent);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, #d97706 10%, var(--sl-color-bg, transparent));
  }

  .rt-title {
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Monaco, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    line-height: 1.25;
    color: var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .rt-under {
    font-size: 0.64rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    line-height: 1.2;
    white-space: nowrap;
    color: var(--sl-color-gray-3, #64748b);
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Narrow viewports: stack the read boxes vertically. The right→left read sockets
     degrade to vertical arcs between stacked boxes (readable, labels still float in
     the gaps), and the client box drops below — the write-back arc just lengthens. */
  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .rt {
      gap: 52px;
    }
    .rt-row {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: stretch;
      gap: 46px;
    }
    .rt-box {
      width: 100%;
    }
    .rt-box--client {
      width: 100%;
    }
    .rt-clientrow {
      justify-content: stretch;
    }
  }
</style>
